Opposition chief Raila Odinga will visit Kerio Valley on Tuesday to console victims of banditry attacks that have left several killed and many injured.Raila's visit comes after the killing of a suspected Pokot bandit in Chesarmat on Friday afternoon.A member of the Marakwet community was injured when bandits attacked Mogil area on Saturday.Read: Pokot bandit shot dead in foiled Kerio Valley raidODM national deputy treasurer Ogla Karani said on Sunday that Raila will also discuss insecurity issues with the locals, following attacks that have taken place since the beginning of the year.Karani will visit accompanied by leaders including Nairobi Governor Evans Kidero and Senators James Orengo (Siaya) and Johnson Muthama(Machakos).Others are MPs John Mbadi (Suba), Gladys Wanga (Homa Bay woman representative), Peter Kaluma (Homa Bay Town) and TJ Kajwang (Ruaraka).On October 23, Raila asked President Uhuru Kenyatta to help curb the banditry attacks, saying they have eroded development gainsAt least 17 people have been shot dead since the skirmishes erupted in March.Marakwet MCAs threatened to lead locals in a march to State House to seek audience with Uhuru on a lasting solution to the menace.The MCA noted Uhuru has powers to ensure lasting peace int he area. We are tired of this problem. We shall be walking with our people all the way to State House to seek the President s help," he said.In a visit to the area on October 27, Deputy President William Ruto announced the recruitment of 40 police reservists to maintain peace and security.But Marakwet professionals said the number was too small for the vast valley. Reports indicated hundreds of people continue to seek refuge in caves for fear of more attacks.More on this: Marakwet MCAs plan walk to State House after fresh clashesAlso read: Banditry has turned Kerio Valley into valley of death